│ THOUGHT: I need to understand the issue first. The problem is that the vector-combine pass is transforming a safe operation into a poisonous one. Specifically,  │
│ it's truncating the shift amount `%y` from `<2 x i32>` to `<2 x i1>` and then performing the lshr on `<2 x i1>`. However, when the original shift amount has     │
│ bits beyond the first bit (like `#x00000001` which is 1), truncating to i1 gives `#x1`, but shifting a 1-bit value by 1 position is undefined/poisonous in LLVM  │
│ because you can't shift a 1-bit value by 1 or more positions (the valid shift amounts for i1 are only 0).                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The transformation is incorrect because it assumes that truncating the shift amount is safe, but it's not when the truncated shift amount is >= the bit width of │
│ the truncated type.                                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ I should look at the vector-combine pass implementation to understand where this transformation is happening.                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                  │
